Laravel Request Lifecycle (Complete Deep Explanation)

Laravel Request Lifecycle explains what happens step-by-step when a user sends a request to a Laravel application and gets a response.

This is one of the MOST IMPORTANT interview + viva + exam topics.

🔷 1. What is Laravel Request Lifecycle?

It is the step-by-step flow of a request from browser → Laravel → response back to browser.

👉 Laravel handles everything internally in a structured pipeline.

🔥 2. Laravel Request Flow (High-Level)
User Request → Public/index.php → Bootstrap → Middleware → Router → Controller → Model → View → Response → User

🔷 3. Step-by-Step Lifecycle (Very Important)
🟢 STEP 1: Request Enters (public/index.php)
Every request starts from:
public/index.php


👉 This is the entry point of Laravel application

What happens here?
Loads Composer autoloader
Starts Laravel application
🟢 STEP 2: Bootstrap Laravel Application

Laravel initializes:

Service container
Configuration files
Environment variables (.env)

👉 File involved:

bootstrap/app.php

🟢 STEP 3: HTTP Kernel Handles Request

Laravel sends request to:

App\Http\Kernel

Kernel does:
Loads global middleware
Prepares request pipeline
🟢 STEP 4: Middleware Execution

Middleware acts as a filter layer

Examples:
Authentication check
Logging
CSRF protection
Flow:
Request → Middleware → Allowed / Blocked


👉 If request fails middleware → it stops here ❌

🟢 STEP 5: Route Matching

Laravel checks:

routes/web.php
routes/api.php

Example:
Route::get('/home', [HomeController::class, 'index']);


👉 Laravel finds which controller to call

🟢 STEP 6: Controller Execution

Controller handles the request logic.

Example:
class HomeController {
    public function index() {
        return view('home');
    }
}


👉 Controller acts as a middle layer

🟢 STEP 7: Model Interaction (Database Layer)

If needed, controller calls Model:

User::all();

Model:
Connects to database
Fetches or stores data
🟢 STEP 8: View Rendering (Blade Engine)

Controller sends data to view:

resources/views/home.blade.php

Example:
return view('home', ['name' => 'John']);

🟢 STEP 9: Response Generation

Laravel converts view into:

HTML response
JSON response (API)
🟢 STEP 10: Response Sent to Browser

Final output is sent back to user:

Browser ← Response ← Laravel

